 ). It appears that three phases of both low settlement intensity and decline in oleiculture (~2500 to 1950 BCE, ~1050 to 840 BCE, and after ~550 BCE; 
 Fig. 3, B and C) are chronologically correlated with the lowest inputs of freshwater from Mount Hermon (
 Fig. 4). This correlation suggests that water supply fluctuation affected settlement density in some way, directly or indirectly. In arid regions (for example, in large parts of Syria and Turkey), the competition for increasingly scarce resources probably led to emigration toward fertile zones like Tel Dan, creating social tensions. Parts of the local population suffering from various forms of predation eventually fled the city, transforming the urban center into a low-density village (
 Fig. 3B).
